  m_Name: Chapter 10
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: 
  chapter: 10
  levelTerms:
  - level: 39
    terms:
    - term: 'Celsius or Centigrade '
      unit: C
      type: 2
      description: 'Is the most widely used temperature scale in the world. It is
        based on both the freezing and boiling points of water under 1 atm of air
        pressure, and it is the easiest to remember. '
      details: "(\u2103), is the most widely used temperature scale in the world.
        It is based on both the freezing and boiling points of water under 1 atm
        of air pressure, and it is the easiest to remember. It scales from zero (0)
        for the freezing point of water, up to a hundred (100) for boiling point
        of water. It is named after Anders Celsius.\n\n(\u2103 \xD7 9 / 5 ) + 32
        = \u2109\n(\u2103 \xD7 1.8) + 32 = \u2109\n"
    - term: 'Fahrenheit Scale '
      unit: "\u2109"
      type: 2
      description: "It is derived from the temperature of a brine solution. Its freezing
        and boiling points are exactly 180\xB0apart."
      details: "(\u2109), named after the proponent Daniel Gabriel Fahrenheit, is
        the temperature scale used by countries who still use the English system,
        like the US. It is derived from the temperature of a brine solution. Its
        freezing and boiling points are exactly 180\xB0apart\n\n(\u2109 - 32) x 5/9
        = \u2103\n\u2109 - 32 / 1.8 = \u2103"
    - term: 'Kelvin Scale '
      unit: K
      type: 1
      description: Is the absolute temperature that is based on the Celsius scale.
        It is used by scientists to show absolute temperatures, for it is precise
        enough to do so.
      details: "As K, is the absolute temperature that is based on the Celsius scale.
        It is used by scientists to show absolute temperatures, for it is precise
        enough to do so.\n\n\U0001D43E = \u2103 + 273"
    - term: 'Rankine '
      unit: R
      type: 2
      description: Is the absolute degree scale used by scientists who uses the Fahrenheit
        scale.
      details: "As R, is the absolute degree scale used by scientists who uses the
        Fahrenheit scale.\n\n\U0001D445 = \u2109 + 459.67"
  - level: 40
    terms:
    - term: Zeroth Law of Thermodynamics
      unit: 
      type: 1
      description: It states that if there are two objects already in equilibrium,
        anything added to that system will also experience thermal equilibrium.
      details: 'The thermometer is not actually taking the temperature of an object
        but is rather taking its own temperature. This is explained by the principle
        of thermal equilibrium, wherein two (2) systems of different temperatures
        must have the same temperature to establish equilibrium. The cooler object
        will get hotter due to heat transfer, making its temperature the same as
        the hotter one which is in thermal contact with. This allows changes to occur
        between the two (2) systems

'
    - term: Linear thermal expansion
      unit: 
      type: 1
      description: 'Is the transfer of heat within the system that is projected in
        one dimension. Simply put, length is the only dimension that changes. '
      details: "This is an example of thermal expansion. Things expand because \r\nof
        heat, like how the hot air balloon flies because hot air expands, becoming
        less dense, hence rising upwards. Or how railroad tracks have gaps, called
        expansion joints, that allow it to expand and contract without buckling,
        or ruining, the tracks."
    - term: Two-dimensional thermal expansion
      unit: 
      type: 1
      description: 'last expansion, just like area, it replaces the length in the
        linear expansion with volume, with a key difference. Instead of the a, it
        uses b, which is the volumetric coefficient of expansion. '
      details: "The transfer of heat within two (2) dimensions, specifically in the
        system\u2019s measured area. Area simply replaces length in the linear thermal
        expansion equation,\n\n"
    - term: Heat
      unit: 
      type: 1
      description: It is caused by kinetic energy from the object
      details: "Is caused by kinetic energy from the object, which we \r\nwill call
        body or system. Heat is a form of energy because it is energy in spontaneous
        transfer caused by changes in temperature. Atoms vibrate at a certain frequency.
        If they receive energy, they vibrate faster, hence allowing the body to expand
        and release their own heat. If that heat is transferred from the body to
        another, losing that energy forces the atoms to vibrate less to conserve,
        allowing them to compact together."
    - term: Calorie
      unit: 
      type: 1
      description: Energy required to increase the temperature of one gram by one
        degree centigrade
      details: 'Calorie (pl. calories) is one of the units of heat, along with Joule.
        Hence, it is the reason we have calorimetry. Calorie is defined as the energy
        required to increase the temperature of one gram by one degree centigrade.
        Thus, calorimetry is defined as the science of measuring heat.

'
    - term: Conduction
      unit: 
      type: 1
      description: 'Is the transfer of heat through direct physical contact between
        two (2) bodies, much like how an electric stove heats a flat Teflon-coated
        pan for frying eggs. '
      details: the transfer of heat through direct physical contact between two (2)
        bodies, much like how an electric stove heats a flat Teflon-coated pan for
        frying eggs. It is the transfer of heat through molecular motion, and goes
        from hot to cold.
    - term: Convection
      unit: 
      type: 1
      description: Is the transfer of heat that involves the movement of mass from
        the body or substance.
      details: The transfer of heat that involves the movement of mass from the body
        or substance. It goes from hot to cold, in which hotter substance rise, pushing
        the colder substance down, where they too will be heated, forming a cycle
        of moving hot and cold masses. This is usually observed in fluids, such as
        air or water, as seen in weather conditions.
    - term: Radiation
      unit: 
      type: 1
      description: 'Is the transfer of heat using the electromagnetic waves, such
        as light. '
      details: The transfer of heat using the electromagnetic waves, such as light.
        But, in order for a body to emit or give off radiation, the temperature must
        be above absolute zero (0 K) to do so. Mathematically,
    - term: Blackbody
      unit: 
      type: 1
      description: If a body can absorb radiation as fast as it can radiate it.
      details: Emissivity always ranges between one (1) and zero (0), with one being
        the representative of the perfect blackbody.
